1 Assumptions

Parametric model assumptions (see Field et al, Chapter 5)
1) Normally distributed
2) Homogeneity of variance across groups
3) Interval or ratio scale
4) Independence

Lets take these one at a time using the Lancaster norms as a test case


1.1 Normality

1.1.1 Histogram of visual salience across English words

Lets first visualize the distribution using a histogram and overlay a normal curve over the distribution. To do this, we need to plot density and not frequency. Lets overlay a normal curve and take a guess. That looks pretty darn normal to me.

ggplot(Lancaster, aes(x = Visual)) + geom_histogram(aes(y = ..density..), 
    colour = "black", fill = "goldenrod2", binwidth = 0.10) + xlab("Likert Rating") + 
    ylab("Density") + jamie.theme + ggtitle("Visual Salience across English Words") + stat_function(fun = dnorm, args = list(mean = mean(Lancaster$Visual), sd= sd(Lancaster$Visual)), color="red", size=1)

1.1.2 QQplot

Lets run a qqplot on all that visual data

qplot(sample = Lancaster$Visual, stat = "qq")

1.1.3 Normality statistics (Shapiro Wilk)

Shapiro Wilk Test null hypothesis is no difference (i.e., normal). It wont work on large samples (>5k) but lets try it out on a smaller distribution we know to be normal

bell <- rnorm(5000, 5, 1)  #here's a fake dataset, sampling 5000 random normally distributed numbers with a mean of 5 and an sd=1
shapiro.test(bell)
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  bell
## W = 0.99966, p-value = 0.5934

1.1.4 Histograms of multiple variables at once

We will use the facet wrap function to do this. Use the long form dataframe

all <- ggplot(long, aes(x = rating), fill=modality) + geom_histogram(aes(y = ..density..), 
   binwidth = 0.10, color="black", fill="goldenrod2") + xlab("Likert Rating") + 
    ylab("Count") + jamie.theme + ggtitle("Histograms of Modalities across English Words") +  facet_wrap(~modality, nrow=2)
all



1.2 Equal Variance

1.2.1 Boxplot for coarse inspection

All levels of the factor variables should have equal variance
First lets coarsely eyeball the variance of the groups by each sensory modality

boxplot(long$rating ~ long$modality, col = "red")

1.2.2 Levene Test

Null hypothesis is the no difference hypothesis

leveneTest(long$rating, long$modality, center = mean)
## Levene's Test for Homogeneity of Variance (center = mean)
##           Df F value    Pr(>F)    
## group      5  4958.3 < 2.2e-16 ***
##       238224                      
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1



1.3 Interval or ratio scale

Self explanatory

1.4 Independence

Self-explanatory. Each word is its own independent observation in the Lancaster normns. There is no temporal autocorrelation.

2 Outliers & Outlier detection

Lets create a univariate distribution shoe sizes. 1.5*IQR is a univariate outlier using the boxplot method. the mean method is >2sds

set.seed(129)
shoes <-  data.frame("sizes"=c(sample(12, 20, replace=T), 30), "type"=rep("nike", 21))
head(shoes)
##   sizes type
## 1     2 nike
## 2     4 nike
## 3     2 nike
## 4     4 nike
## 5     2 nike
## 6     7 nike
ggplot(shoes, aes(x=type, y=sizes), fill=sizes) + geom_point(shape = 21, color = "black", size = 2.3, alpha = 0.6, position = position_jitter(w = 0.03, h = 0)) + ylab("shoe sizes") + jamie.theme

summary(shoes)

2.1 Eliminating outliers z>2 (one tailed get rid of big shoes)

We can just throw them out by filtering or applying a simple if then statement

shoes.small <- shoes.z %>% filter(zsize <= 2)  #creates a new dataframe returning only shoe sizes z<2 in the original distribution
summary(shoes.small)
##      sizes         type          zsize.V1

2.2 Eliminating outliers -2>z>2 (two-tailed get rid of smallest and largest shoes)

This is essentially a band pass filter that knocks out the largest and smallest shoes. Lets create a new vector that only has shoes

shoes.mid <- shoes.z %>% filter(zsize <= abs(1))  #creates a new dataframe returning only shoe #sizes within the central range of +/- 1 sd of the mean

3 Transformations

Need to be done on all the variables not just one. Lets look at the olfactory ratings.

ggplot(Lancaster, aes(x = Olfactory)) + geom_histogram(aes(y = ..density..), 
    colour = "black", fill = "green", binwidth = 0.10) + xlab("Likert Rating") + 
    ylab("Density") + jamie.theme + ggtitle("Olfactory Salience across English Words") + stat_function(fun = dnorm, args = list(mean = mean(Lancaster$Olfactory), sd= sd(Lancaster$Olfactory)), color="black", size=1)

3.1 Natural log transform

For illustrative purposes I have created a new dataframe with just smell and visual ratings on English words. This transform is good for positively skewed data long tail to right. Theres a problem here in that we have some zero observations

brief <- Lancaster %>% select(1,6,7)
length(which(brief$Olfactory==0))  #counts the number of rows with a 0 observation
## [1] 8993
brief$log <- log(brief$Olfactory + 1) #log is natural log, log10 is log base 10, this adds 1 so that there is never a 0 observation
ggplot(brief, aes(x = log)) + geom_histogram(aes(y = ..density..), 
    colour = "black", fill = "green", binwidth = 0.10) + 
    ylab("Density") + jamie.theme + ggtitle("Log olfactory Salience") + stat_function(fun = dnorm, args = list(mean = mean(brief$log), sd= sd(brief$log)), color="black", size=1)

3.2 Square root transformation

You dont have to worry about zeros

brief$sqrt <- sqrt(brief$Olfactory)
head(brief)

ggplot(brief, aes(x = sqrt)) + geom_histogram(aes(y = ..density..),

    ylab("Density") + jamie.theme + ggtitle("Sqrt olfactory Salience") + stat_function(fun = dnorm, args = list(mean = mean(brief$sqrt), sd= sd(brief$sqrt)), color="black", size=1)

3.3 Reciprocal transformation

Doesnt work when there are zeros in the denominator

brief$recip <- 1/(brief$Olfactory+1)
